node.title: Simulation stuck on really small time steps

node.bodyText:
Hello
What does your TimeStepper block look like? In the Executioner
I see no reason why the time step cannot be grown, the solves are converging
Guillaume

Hello @GiudGiud ,
I'm using the IterationAdaptiveDT in the executioner:
[Executioner]
  type = Transient
  solve_type = Newton
  end_time = 2.4e3 #3600 
  automatic_scaling = true
  [TimeStepper]
    type = IterationAdaptiveDT
    dt = 1e1           
    optimal_iterations = 10
  []
   nl_abs_tol = 1e-5
   nl_rel_tol = 1e-5
        l_tol = 1e-5
[]

That seems like the problem but the parameters should have been fine. At 4 nonlinear iterations, the time step should grow. Between 8 (=10 - 20% of 10) and 12 non linear iterations, it should stabilize.
You can try another heuristic for this problem:
this one https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/timesteppers/SolutionTimeAdaptiveDT.html
or this one
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/timesteppers/PostprocessorDT.html with https://mooseframework.inl.gov/source/postprocessors/PseudoTimestep.html

node.title: Specifying IC's Over 2-D Domain
node.bodyText:
I have found question #21209 asked about using a .csv file to specify IC's and I have a similar question.
Suppose I run a PF simulation to steady-state that yields some equilibrium concentration c(x,y). Now what I would like to do is take this equilibrium concentration and import back into MOOSE as the IC for concentration, c(x,y,0).
I see something called Polycrystal Initial Conditions also?
Is there a way to do this thx!

I think I found it here...
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/syntax/ICs/index.html

If it s coming from MOOSE into MOOSE, then we usually just use a SolutionUserObject with a SOlutionIC. No need for a CSV.
CSV will be helpful if you are trying to process the field in an intermediate step. ANd then PropertyReadFile / PiecewiseConstantFromCSV is what I use
OK I will try thx!

node.title: Correct notation for defining variables
node.bodyText:
I am a bit confused about the correct notation for the definition of variables. For example here
https://mooseframework.inl.gov/getting_started/examples_and_tutorials/examples/ex01_inputfile.html
variables are defined as
[./variable_name]
...
[../]
but in most other places, they are defined as follows
[variable_name]
...
[]
What's the difference between the two ways to define variables?

Hello
Those are the same in MOOSE.
The ../ and ./ are a legacy syntax but it wont error or complain if you use it.
Guillaume

node.title: SideIntegralVariablePostprocessor over a Specified Boundary
node.bodyText:
Suppose I am using SideIntegralVariablePostprocessor over an edge of a 2-D object.
Is there a way to integrate only over a specified portion of this edge. For example, if the edge is y =10 for x = 0 to x = 50, could the integration be done only over x = 10 to x = 20?
Thank you!

Hello
Two options I can think off:


use a parsedGenerateSideset to create a subset of the edge in a sideset and then use that sideset in the postprocessor


use the new mesh divisions system to create a grid excluding the portion you dont care about then make a new postprcoessor that integrates over a side in a mesh division


Guillaume

OK thanks I figured I would try parsedGenerateSideset and began by modifying my current mesh statement to give it a name. That new code is shown too and I get this error, do I need to register something thx!
*** ERROR ***
Task add_mesh_generator is not registered to build MooseMesh derived objects
[Mesh] type = GeneratedMesh dim = 2 elem_type = QUAD4 nx = 80 ny = 20 xmin = 0 xmax = 40 ymin = 0 ymax = 10 uniform_refine = 2 []
[Mesh] [structure] type = GeneratedMesh dim = 2 elem_type = QUAD4 nx = 80 ny = 20 xmin = 0 xmax = 40 ymin = 0 ymax = 10 uniform_refine = 2 [] []

do this instead
[Mesh] 
  [gmg]
    type = GeneratedMeshGenerator
    dim = 2
    elem_type = QUAD4
    nx = 80
    ny = 20
    xmin = 0
    xmax = 40
    ymin = 0
    ymax = 10
  []
  uniform_refine = 2
[]

the problem is that the old "all my paramenters directly in [Mesh]" syntax only works with a single mesh object. And here you want two, once for generating the mesh and one for modifying the sideset. So you need to update to the new nested MeshGenerator syntax
[Mesh]
  [name of the mesh generator]
    type ....
  []
  [name of the second mesh generator]
    type ....
  []
[]

OK thanks I tried this below and I get an error about adding periodic BC's I am using these on two of my state variables?
*** ERROR ***
Couldn't auto-detect a paired boundary for use with periodic boundary conditions
[Mesh]  [gmg] type = GeneratedMeshGenerator dim = 2 elem_type = QUAD4 nx = 80 ny = 20 xmin = 0 xmax = 40 ymin = 0 ymax = 10 [] [sideset] type = ParsedGenerateSideset input = gmg combinatorial_geometry = 'y = 10 & 4 < x < 6' new_sideset_name = new_integration_domain [] uniform_refine = 2 []

this error is not coming from the mesh block. It s coming from your periodic BC block.
Can you pass more parameters to the Periodic BC block to avoid using the automatic dectection?

OK I am looking at the documentation and want to make sure I understand setting PBC's. Are the primary and secondary names of edges in this particular example, 3 and 1 for the x-direction an these edges 40 units apart and 0 and 2 for the y-direction and these edges are also 40 units apart? Thx!
I also ran my code temporarily without PBS's and the parsedGenerateSideset  worked.
[BCs]
  [./Periodic]
    [./x]
      variable = u
      primary = 3
      secondary = 1
      translation = '40 0 0'
    [../]

    [./y]
      variable = u
      primary = 0
      secondary = 2
      translation = '0 40 0'
    [../]
  [../]
[]

Primary and secondary are the names of the edges (sidesets) indeed.
Can you use the names instead? Left and right should be easy to pair for example

OK that works I and my results match the auto PBC however I noticed that if I set the new sideset to a small fraction of the initial sideset dimension the integrated current does not change, I was expecting that it would scale with the length of the integration domain. Any suggestions thx!

so it's detecting more than the new sideset in a way? It's using the old sideset for the boundary condition?
Are you restricting it to a small fraction on both sides of the periodic boundary?

I am integrating current density over the top edge of a 2-D thin film, the goal was to integrate current density only over a specified region of this top edge. This top edge is defined at y = 10 and over 0 < x <  10.
If the new sideset is define y = 10 and then 0 < x < 5 I was expecting to see current drop by approximately 2x but it remained the same as integrating over the old sideset.
How do restrict it to a small fraction on both sides of the periodic boundary? What does that mean? Thx!
  [sideset]
    type = ParsedGenerateSideset
    input = gmg
    combinatorial_geometry = 'y = 10 & 0 < x < 5'
    new_sideset_name = new_integration_domain
  []

[Postprocessors]
  [top_edge_current]
  type = SideIntegralVariablePostprocessor
  variable = J_mag
  boundary = new_integration_domain
  []
[]

I am actually not sure fparser likes " 'y = 10 & 0 < x < 5'", for two reasons. Can you try this for the combinatorial geometry
 'y < 10.0000001 & y > 9.999999 & 0 < x & x < 5'

then can you check the mesh file to make sure it looks like half of the sideset
btw I see your posts are formatted with a single backquote. If you use three backquotes instead it looks a lot better. I just edited your post
OK cool thank you let me try and I will use 3x quotes I was wondering how to do that.
OK that works like I expected thank you!

node.title: If statement in parsed function
node.bodyText:
Hi,
I’m trying to use an ‘if’ statement to define the following statements in a parsed function:
if t < 30, then 10
elseif t is between 30 and 40, then 5
elseif  t is between 40 and 60, then 10
else 5.
I tried using the following, but it doesn’t work. Please, help.
value = 'if(t <= 30, 10, if(t <= 40, 5.0),  if(t <= 60, 10.0, 5.0))'

The if command always take 3 arguments. Try this:
value = 'if(t <= 30, 10, if(t <= 40, 5.0,  if(t <= 60, 10.0, 5.0)))'
That works great! Thanks, @ajacquey
can this parsed function also be expressed in that way ?

hello
Yes, you can nest if conditions to achieve this
expression = 'if(t <= 1500, if(x <= 1500, 900,  0), if(x <= 1500, 100.0, if(x < 2000, 200, 300))))'
Thank you very much. Did there any files tell us how to use this ParsedFunction more details?

Hello
There's the documentation for fparser which we rely on in the backend
